fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
The successor universee \mathcal {U}^+ of a universe \mathcal {U} is defined using universe postulate
    with the following contexts:
             \vdash \mathcal {U}\space \space \text {type}\quad  X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \mathcal {T}(X)\space \space \text {type}     
    It therefore contains the type \mathcal {U} as well as type in \mathcal {U}, in the following sense
             \begin {align*}             &\vdash \check {\mathcal {U}}:\mathcal {U}^+\\              &\vdash \mathcal {T}^+(\check {\mathcal {U}})\equiv \mathcal {U}\space \text {type}\\             &X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \check {\mathcal {T}}(X):\mathcal {U}^+\\              &X:\mathcal {U}\vdash \mathcal {T}^+(\check {\mathcal {T}}(X))\equiv \mathcal {T}(X)\space \text {type}          \end {align*}

We assume that there're enough universe, i.e.,
    for every finite list of types in context 
             \Gamma _1\vdash  A_1\space \space \text {type},\cdots ,\Gamma _n\vdash  A_n\space \space \text {type}     
    there is a universe \mathcal {U} that contains each A_i in the sense that \mathcal {U} comes equipped with
             \Gamma _i\vdash \check {A_i}:\mathcal {U}     
    for which the following judgement holds:
             \Gamma _i \vdash \mathcal {T}(\check {A_i})\equiv  A_i\space \space \text {type}

